The Literary Magic of Harry Potter
Princeton — — This summer, readers around the world celebrated the 20th anniversary of the first book in J.K. Rowling's Harry Potter series — — Harry Potter and the Philosopher's Stone (renamed Harry Potter and the Sorcerer's Stone in the United States) at literary festivals and bookstores. They had every reason to celebrate.
Since the young wizard first appeared on June 26, 1997, this "Boy Who Lived" has become a "symbol of resilience and perseverance."
Over the past 20 years, the Harry Potter series has expanded to include seven books, been translated into more than 70 languages, and has sold a combined total of 450 million copies.
The eight films based on this book have grossed a cumulative total of $7 billion, while Harry Potter-themed toys and merchandise have generated an additional $7 billion in revenue.
It is hard for people of a certain age and with a literary mindset to imagine a day when global audiences were not enchanted by Rowling's works.
Therefore, I am still amazed every time I recall my students' poor reaction to the book "Harry Potter and the Philosopher's Stone" in the fall of 1999, when I included this book in the syllabus for my popular literature course at Princeton University. I have been teaching the "Bestsellers in America" series course since 1993.
This course studies popular works from the 17th century up to the present, inviting students to think about why and in what ways these bestsellers have attracted their audiences.
At the end of each semester, I ask my students to select a final work that represents popular taste.
In 1999, they chose the first "Harry Potter" novel.
That year, the Potter fever hit the American coast fiercely.
In June, the American publisher of the series urgently released the hardcover edition of the second book in the Harry Potter series, "Harry Potter and the Chamber of Secrets," in bookstores.
The institution also published the third book in the series, "Harry Potter and the Prisoner of Azkaban," on September 8, as well as the paperback edition of "Harry Potter and the Sorcerer's Stone."
By the end of the month, Rowling's novel had taken the top three spots on The New York Times bestseller list, and the paperback edition of "Harry Potter and the Sorcerer's Stone" had topped the paperback book sales chart.
Time magazine even put this bespectacled wizard on its cover.
Harry Potter's image is everywhere in sight.
My students were eager to know why such a frenzy had occurred.
My goodness, they were utterly disappointed.
In their view, the Harry Potter series was nothing more than second-rate nonsense, which could not hold a candle to the series they cherished from their childhood, such as The Chronicles of Narnia or The Lord of the Rings.
Although their childhood had only just passed a few years ago, they criticized Harry Potter just like many notorious adult critics, calling it "made-up," "poorly written," "clichéd," and "boring."

In their view, Harry had neither miracles, nor wit, nor warmth.
The students' aversion surprised me, but in hindsight, there was nothing surprising about it.
Although adults had always constituted a significant portion of the Harry Potter audience, these students were precisely at the wrong age to objectively understand the Harry Potter phenomenon.
They were past the age of accepting new children's books, but at the same time too young to have their own children (at that time, I had just had my own child), and they eagerly insisted that although the Harry series was now popular, it would soon be forgotten by people.
In the fall of the next year, which was 2000, the next batch of students also chose "Harry Potter and the Philosopher's Stone" as their final analysis work, just like their predecessors, they confidently rejected this work.
Let us fast forward to the spring of 2007.
After setting the course aside for a few years, I once again taught "Bestsellers in America."
When the students chose their final analysis work, they chose "Harry Potter and the Philosopher's Stone."
And I prepared to welcome their criticisms.
But this time, their comments were very positive.
These were a new generation of students, born between 1986 and 1989, who first read Rowling's works not as college students, but as teenagers in their teens, just beginning to enter adolescence. This meant that they had grown up together with Harry, Ron, and Hermione as young adults.
The same thing happened in the fall of 2010.
For these students, "We grew up with Harry Potter" had become a motto, not just a label.
Would Harry ever fade from memory?
As long as we are alive, it is impossible.
Since 2010, I have taught the bestsellers course twice, and both times the students chose non-Harry Potter novels for their final reviews.
Was it because they were tired of Potter?
From the reviews that the Harry Potter series received in another course I taught, "Children's Literature," where I also taught Rowling's works, this seems unlikely.
Now, I choose to include a Harry Potter novel in the syllabus, but I did not choose "Harry Potter and the Philosopher's Stone," instead I chose "Harry Potter and the Prisoner of Azkaban" — this is my favorite among the seven Harry Potter novels, marking the series' transition from children's literature to young adult fiction, and it features complex depictions of loyalty, betrayal, anger, and compassion.
Many of my students also loved this book the most.
But how long can the popularity of the Harry Potter series last?
Every time I teach children's literature, I first conduct a poll: "Which books on the syllabus did you read during your childhood?"
In 2010, 86% of the students had read "Harry Potter and the Prisoner of Azkaban."
In 2012, this figure rose to 94%.
But in the following years, the percentage continued to decline — — 87% in 2014, and it dropped to 81% in 2016.
These are not scientific figures, I know.
But I am curious: next spring when I teach "Children's Literature" again, will the percentage of students who have read Harry Potter drop below 80%?
Will the facts prove that the students from 1999 to 2000 were right, that Harry Potter's status is continuously declining and will never become a timeless classic?
Or is there a balance point ahead where the percentage can stabilize and stop declining?
Perhaps Harry's 40th anniversary will tell us the answer.
Until then, I am happy to continue inviting him into my classroom.
